Patients will receive access to “transformative” treatment for HIV prevention from September following a decision of the Supreme Court on the financing of NHS.
The English National Health Service (NSH) has announced that the pre-expoure propylaxis (PreEP) pill, which is used before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86%, will be offered through the health service to around 10,000 patients within a three-year trial period.
The NSH agreed to finance the trial period after the appeal court supported the decision of the Supreme Court last year, stating that the NHS had financial resources to pay for the PrEP despite the statement that the cure should be financed by the local authorities.
The decision announced on Thursday was taken by the NHS of England from the mouth of CEO Simon Stevens as a “significant intervention” while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a “deciding moment”.
The clinics of sexual health in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to start receiving patients. Other clinics will join in October and a full implementation will take place throughout England by April 2018.
Pre-expoure prophylaxis (PreEP) is an HIV medicine given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PreEP significantly reduces the risk of transmission of HIV between patients at risk.
The PreEP application before sex means that there are enough specific medicines in the patient’s body to prevent infection.
These medicines can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Tested patients include homosexual or bisexual men, transsexual people and people with HIV positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics shall designate eligible participants who sign consent to participation in the testing, including men, women, transsexual people and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by the appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with GP in the UK can also apply to their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential participation in testing.
The program will be issued by taxpayers at £10 million and NHS England has signed a contract this week to distribute medicines after obtaining an international public contract.
The trial period is proposed for the collection of clinical evidence and the assessment of the full potential of the PREP, its purpose, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: ‘This important intervention should complement and fully exploit the ever-growing and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It's another milestone in over 30 years of trying to stop one of the biggest challenges to human health.'
Deborah Gold, NAT Executive Director (National Aids Trust) said: “We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PreEP is administered correctly and at risk to patients, it will offer the possibility of changing the HIV epidemic of England.
NSH will offer from September patients at high risk of HIV infection a new powerful instrument, which is individually controlled and is not subject to the need to persuade their partner, leading to an improvement in the quality of many lives.
We accept this declaration with pleasure.'
Ian Green, CEO of Terrence Higgins Trust, said: ‘ Priority number one must be a quick test deployment across the country; we must ensure that it is accessible to every patient.
