A Becoming Resemblance: Artist creates portraits using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of one of the rooms of the New York Fridman Gallery is placed just a few faces of different skin shades - white, black and brown - hung from the ceiling on the wires. Each of them seems to have fallen out of the eye of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were made by the artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from the oral and hair swabs that Chelsea Manning sent her.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth Prison, where an ex-analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for unauthorized disclosure of secret cabograms on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which was launched on August 2, bears the name A Being Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, which combines his experience with technology, IT and art, and Manning, a transsexual and pioneer dissident, whose punishment Obama reduced three days before leaving the post of President of the USA.
The algorithmic DNA analysis of Manning and the use of 30 portraits to illustrate what a person would look like with this genotype, created Dewey-Hagborg's sharp, if not intellectual commentary on the submissiveness of DNA - as well as many ways that DNA can be interpreted - and the inseparable determinism of these interpretations as well as identities.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, has been talking about being a woman since she was a young woman. She was convicted in 2013 on the basis of 20 charges, including violations of six spy laws, computer fraud, and theft.
All of her photos were held by prison staff. Only one lower quality black and white photograph has escaped in the public, which Manning, visibly concerned, is sitting in the driver's seat in a platinum blonde wig that she is now associated with.
In 2015, positive reactions to the Dewey-Hagborg project from 2012 Stranger Visions continued.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg has used various forensic objects - such as cigarette and gum nails - to create a picture of possible forms of these people.
And at this time, she received an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They were going to interview Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted to complete the article with a portrait," Dewey-Hagborg explained on the occasion of the opening of the new exhibition.
However, visits and photography were not allowed, so they turned to Chelsea asking if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her trapped muse became friends within two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic book called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, who presented a vision of what would have happened if Chelsea had been pardoned and could have attended the exhibition in person.
Indeed, President Obama, a few days after the release of the comic book, asked for Manning's release, which was a welcome change after several insufferable years spent in a military prison in Kansas.
It is interesting, indeed, that the exhibition is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is at war with people seeking to publish government information and transgender soldiers while trying to find new ways to incite hatred in the areas that he should support.
In answer to a question about this special timing, Dewey-Hagborg stated that "everything is happening for a reason".
Under a statement by an artist on one of the walls of the gallery, Manning calls for her huge signature (the letter "i" in her last name is worded with a heart) after the end of "self-employed fraction, which is based on sex, race, sexuality and culture".
On the opposite side there are sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - a centipede of letters C, G and A recorded in pencil.
By classifying 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to the sophisticated scientific dictionary of the artist) Dewey-Hagborg wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we are all together.
"I hope that people will take away from this, that our genome does not matter who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it in their own way," said Dewey-Hagborg. Her work Spurious Memories from 2007 on the subject of video is also visible.
"THE DAY tells many different stories, this is 30 of them."
The last specimen of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is the only page from the above graphic novel.
It depicts Manning, which appears as King Kong from the United States Disiplinary Barracks prison with a megaphone in his hand.
"As soon as they stop you from speaking, they win," it says.
"Never be silenced."
“It’s a direct transcript from one of the letters,” she said.
"When I think about it, my skin's creeping."
Manning has so far not personally visited the exhibition - which was foretold in the comic book - but when it does, she will be welcomed in the middle of the room by her masks, her own genome forms, arranged as a crowd of Protestants.
Which was also the purpose of the exhibition, including almost 160 cm of the high statue of Manning, to which its genetic haplogroup is recorded by pencil.
"In the past, they were placed on the walls, but this time I wanted the feeling of the crowd to come out of them," Dewey-Hagborg said about the portraits.
"I wanted the impression of mass movement, which takes the form of Chelsea and liberates it."
