startups that will help your company not to become another Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the satisfaction rate of her staff's e-commerce startup, but she didn't find an adequate survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, useless, or even misleading.
And even though she promised the anonymity of the survey, some employees expressed their distrust in the entire process.
"I looked for consistency and objectivity," said Errett, owner of the hair care company Madison Reed, based in San Francisco, employing 75 people.
So she asked for help from outside.
New start-ups from the field of human resources are constantly emerging on the market to help companies survey their employees’ satisfaction.
By creating and licensing software with a particular intention of measuring employees' obligations, start-ups enable companies to make quick votes, target specific teams and demographic groups, and also offer absolute anonymity of employees and a hotline for complaints, and in some cases also allow informants to circumvent their superiors and contact the director directly.
"There are tools on the market like Strava and Fitbit, which follow your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of the Glint startup based in Reedwood City.
Errett said that Glint has gained greater awareness of what her employees think and feel in three years.
In addition to quick surveys and votes of specific teams, Glint offers a temperature map of the company and a common overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of low-rated managers - which allows the user to work on the correction.
Companies are beginning to realize that it is necessary to take care of the culture of the working environment - in case they become another Uber - who is thrown away in scandals after the former employee posted a post on his blog describing the company environment and harassing employees who dare to speak openly.
For startups like Glint, demand for surveys of corporate culture is a lucrative business opportunity.
According to Let's Talk Payments, which deals with technical and financial progress, the value of the global control, regulation and compliance sector can exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
The startup Converter of Denver, Colorado, who helps companies to prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small increase in interest and activity at the beginning of the year, just before the scandals of Uber.
Almost 600 Converter clients include Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber has recently accepted under his wing.
Like Glint, the Converter allows companies to send customised flash surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text line that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
If the Director-General is involved in the problem, the complaints shall be sent directly to the Governing Board.
"The Court of Justice has authorised regulators," said Patrick Quinlan, founder and executive director of the Converter startup.
If the company is convicted of improper treatment of its employees or of non-ethical behaviour - and if the regulators do not act - it may face costly consequences as a result of boycotting customers, exhaustion of employees or legal proceedings, Quinlan added.
The Ruby Tuesday restaurant network, which employs over 25,000 people across 500 locations, uses Converter for more than a year to raise employees' awareness of corporate principles and procedures and to ensure an easy way to contact corporate management.
Earlier, if an employee wanted to report any problems, he had to track the phone number or e-mail to company management, officially file a complaint and hope for a successful solution.
Often it was a discouraging and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, Secretary General of Ruby Tuesday, according to which there had previously been no reliable way of monitoring employee complaints.
Now that the company is using the Converter, quick detection and resolution of problems that have never gone to managers, sitting in offices, miles away from the actual solution to complaints - such as discrimination, harassment or unfair treatment.
"This is closer to a holistic, overall view of employees' experience," said Vitrano, who manages Ruby Tuesday's risk management group.
"At the same time, we protect shareholders from court disputes by employees."
The companies stopped taking the ethics, values and participation of employees on a light scale in 2002 after the accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed after Enron fell in the case of the abuse of the ethical rights of employees, Quinlan said.
But only when “the social media lit up the whole thing, ” did companies begin to realize that they could not simply hide their skeletons in the closet in the online world.
"Before people started using technology to monitor ethics, they relied on faith," Quinlan added.
Glint and Converter offer their software in the form of a service for which companies pay regular fees.
It is a business model and an opportunity approved by bold equity investors, who supported both startups.
As part of his February campaign, the Converter selected $10 million in total from companies such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital and finally raised a capital of $47 million.
In November, Glint received $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners and gained $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the mutual nature of companies, culture and risk capital.
A growing number of research shows that today’s employees expect more than ever from their workplace.
And in competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, the main advantage is not high wages and interesting projects.
Employees want to see that they are received and appreciated and that they are devoted their time to a society that is pursuing a positive mission.
"If people are happy in their work, they feel that their voice is heard and that their work is rewarding, they seek the success of society," said Nina McQueen, Vice President of Global Benefits and Employee Benefits of LinkedIn, who is also using the Converter and Glint.
Investors earn if companies and companies thrive if their employees are satisfied.
And when an analytical tool appears on the market to ensure employees' commitment and commitment to society, it is no wonder that there are many investors who will support this effort.
It is important, according to experts in the work culture, to have data on the satisfaction of employees.
But the data itself is pointless unless society takes the necessary steps.
The fact is that once the company requests feedback from its employees, there may be major changes.
And if change does not happen quickly - in the worst case, at all - it can cause disappointment and disinterest of the staff.
"When you ask for 4,000 opinions, you must be prepared for 4000 conversations," said Russell Raath, Director of Consulting at Kotter International, who witnessed many companies relying too much on data alone.
“ As soon as you don’t get to the end of things, the employees start asking themselves, ‘ Did they hear me?
Are they interested in me?
And if not, then why should I care?"
Madison Reed, who is currently doing a regular survey every month between employees, is able to solve the problem thanks to Glint in one day, said Errett.
After the assembly of feedback from employees who were frustrated by slow decision-making and the quality of communication, Errett was able to reorganise several teams within the society and start training communication to resolve the problem successfully.
Ruby Tuesday receives a very important view of its employees and hopes that in the long term it will achieve high employment in the field known for frequent redundancies.
"If you are not seeking to create a transparent working environment, employees will not believe you," added Vitrano.
“And once you start losing employees, you lose customers.
And with the outflow of customers, the whole company will fail."
