"A look at the writing of a man who is 300 years after his death fascinates me," says Rhodes with a serious face.
"When I hold a letter in my hand, I feel a personal connection."
A graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of families who resided in Scotland Castle from the Middle Ages to the Eduardian period. Each story is illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
However, it is not the first Rhodes book inspired by archives: it is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stores (2014), a collection of inspired documents from the British Library - a project that was very emotional to him.
"I was interested in a thumbprint on a letter that was written by a double agent in the 1970s who worked for Jacobites," he said.
