Some stories in the book use the castle as a reflection bridge and drill deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the English Uprising in 1381.
"I found a record of a rebellion at the 1380 Castle, which was called Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex in the book," said Rhodes.
“The English Uprising actually started in this area and I thought that rebellion is a good starting point.
Maybe in the end he's connected."
Other stories are closely linked to the history of the castle - for example The Priest, who tells the story of a Jesuit priest whose family was hidden by Darrell for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler, a 18th - century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled the coffin with stones (which was discovered several years after the coffin was discovered).
Rhodes’ favorite family is Darrell’s: “I was intrigued by the male generation — then men were always in debt and spent money on things they couldn’t afford.
The different generations of the Darrell family solved this by marrying rich or old ladies - I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to confuse their heirs' heads."
He's been searching for Rhodes for more adventures with the end of his stay at the castle.
He recently returned from a two-week stand in the Finnish wilderness, where he inspired his next book on Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century, which was absorbed by nature.
But it's a strange place for Scotney.
"I was sad when I left," he said.
"I said to myself, "Now I'm going to get the hell back to real life."
