The White House Requisition cost tax payers thousands of dollars
The White House's decision to arrive with the Navy helicopter to South Lawn to celebrate the American manufacturing industry last month came at $24,000, according to the Navy records issued by TIME weekly.
The green white helicopter Sikorsky VH-3D, also called Marine One in the presence of the President on board, was the highlight of the program of July 17 in the White House, which was a show of American design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and several senior White House officials were watching a product show from all 50 countries.
The helicopter from Connecticut was displayed next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi.
A military officer of the White House issued a partial order, or FRAGO, requesting the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the helicopter landing on South Lawn in the context of an “extraordinary” event, reported the records of the Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) - units responsible for the administration of the helicopter.
"I wanted to make sure that you were aware of such an important event," wrote Commander HMX-1 in his e-mail to his superior, representative of the Navy commander for the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter will arrive at South Lawn on July 17 at around 7:00 p.m. on the occasion of the show, the beginning of which is scheduled for 3:00 p.m. and will remain in place until the entire site was fully cleared, scheduled between 6:00 p.m. and 21:00 p.m.
It was further stated in the e-mail that if there was a delay in leaving the White House, a replacement crew will be sent for return flight due to the working time regulation.
The original crew remained on the scene that night, along with the helicopter, along with the security forces.
The records - which the TIME weekly received - did not indicate whether the second crew was finally dispatched.
Hatch Act prevents government officials from using government property for political purposes.
Records suggest that HMX-1 is investigating a possible infringement of this Regulation.
“We were wondering if it was a breach of Hatch Act and we were assured that everything was fine,” wrote the commander.
"It sounds like you were blocked," the deputy commander replied.
This show "Made in America" was marked by the White House as an official event, and Hatch Act would not apply to it.
But even official events have political subtexts.
In his participation in the events, the President was promoting a health reform that went through the Senate and talked about trying to keep government regulations under control.
The use of means of air transport such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them to travel.
However, their presence is unusual because of presentational reasons.
Trump ordered control in February after the President's plane was in the background at his first meeting in the Melbourne campaign in Florida. His Twitter account is clouded by complaints about the use of his predecessor's presidential aircraft.
“The White House is pleased with the “Made in America” show, which introduced products from all 50 countries made by Americans from American materials,” said the press secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 helicopter crews often train landings in the Washington area and South Lawn and practice any arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit at the beginning of July in Germany, HMX-1 carried out 58 training landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America show was part of the current training of the crew, said the state official.
On the same day, the helicopter unit flew into the "non-presidential support missions" for another eleven hours.
The White House stated that no other props were paid out of taxpayers' money.
The spokesperson Sikorsky stated that the company had no interest in any way in the negotiations for the exhibition of helicopters in South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep records of the budget for presidential flights and the exact cost of the show is difficult, according to the Navy's comments.
According to the Ministry of Defence, the hourly price for the fiscal year 2017, the compensation of DoD expenditure for VH-3D 24 380$ per flight hour.
The unit records indicate the time 30 minutes from the Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico base in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of helicopters are well below that amount.
"Indicating taxpayers' costs on the basis of reimbursement estimates is very misleading," said Walters.
‘These estimates include staff, maintenance and many other hidden costs included in the annual costs.’
According to the 2015 RAND study, DoD's reimbursements do not include staff costs, but include fuel, maintenance and contractual costs.
The press secretary of the White House, Sean Spicer, defended the use of a helicopter for the purpose of the show.
“The idea of the show this week is to introduce products produced in the USA,” Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the State of Connecticut are very proud to contribute to the defence of our state and to provide work for hundreds, if not thousands of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of helicopters and other military facilities, whose production is attended by countless American citizens.
This fact is to be recalled."
It is not clear whether Trump was also on a helicopter during his tour of South Lawn. It is only possible to say that he sat behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back in the White House, Trump approached Sikorsky's representative and made jokes with the media about his own fleet of products.
"I know Sikorsky very well," said the president, "I own three."
